summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1493: Cinccino (Black & White)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1493: Cinccino (Black & White)
body:
The Black & White games had a lot of Pokemon that were basically new takes on the original Pokemon. Cinccino didn’t fit that too well, but the card ended up being Jungle Wigglytuff. It had a faster, stronger version of Do the Wave that was more efficient to keep up with a much stronger game. Now all Cinccino had to do was to try to live up to the standards of a card that was one of the best of its time. Not an easy task.

90 HP wasn’t all that rare for a Stage 1 Pokemon, but it was low enough to have to worry about getting taken down quite a bit. The HP number combined with a Fighting Weakness meant that the likes of Donphan, Magnezone, Reshiram, Zekrom, Terrakion, and a bunch of Pokemon EX could KO. This made Cinccino pretty hard to use against a ton of good decks. It only needed that single Energy to retreat if it somehow got the chance, at least.

Tail Slap existed. 2 coin flips and 20 damage for each heads for a Colorless Energy? No thanks.

Do the Wave was special. It only needed 2 Colorless Energy, making it a fit for the HGSS-On format that had Double Colorless Energy available. 20 damage for each Benched Pokemon could add up quickly. You had to surround Cinccino with all the big Basic Pokemon out there, like the dragons, Tornadus, Terrakion, or Pokemon EX. That could get you to 100 damage, which was really impressive for the cost.

Cinccino had a cheap attack with the potential for a lot of damage in a format where there was no lack of good Basic Pokemon to use. So why didn’t it get more traction? It was a Stage 1 without a ton of HP, meaning that it could fall really easily and needed an extra turn to set up. On top of that, those Basic Pokemon that were so good tended to be better on their own than Cinccino could be. It was somewhat workable since this was still 100 damage for a Double Colorless Energy when all went well. Being worse than just using the Pokemon it wanted to pair with meant this was no Jungle Wigglytuff after all.
